"script": "Deep in the Australian forest lives a bird that can imitate almost any sound it hears. The lyrebird starts with the calls of other birds, stringing dozens together in a single song. But it doesn't stop there. It can copy a camera shutter, a car alarm, even a chainsaw cutting through trees. And it does this so perfectly that you genuinely can't tell the difference. Males use these stolen sounds to impress females, building a soundtrack of the entire forest. One bird was recorded mimicking workmen's tools so well, it sounded like a construction site in the wild.",
